  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Violent discipline declined, but remains common",
        "body": "Any violent discipline method was reported for 54.7 percent of children aged 1 to 14 in 2025, down from 58.8 percent in 2022. Psychological aggression fell from 48.4 to 43.6 percent, any physical punishment fell from 39.1 to 36.1 percent, and severe physical punishment fell from 3.4 to 2.0 percent. The direction is downward across the violent discipline measures, but the national level remains high."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Non-violent discipline increased as violent discipline fell",
        "body": "Only non-violent discipline rose from 35.7 percent in 2022 to 39.0 percent in 2025. That movement is consistent with the decline in violent discipline, though the measures do not imply a simple one-for-one replacement. The national picture is better than in 2022 but still mixed: non-violent discipline is below 40 percent, while any violent discipline remains above half of children."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Davao Region and Cagayan Valley are the highest regional points",
        "body": "Davao Region had the highest any violent discipline level at 70.9 percent, followed by Cagayan Valley at 66.8 percent and Bicol Region at 66.4 percent. Davao also had the highest psychological aggression at 60.3 percent, while Cagayan Valley had the highest physical punishment at 47.2 percent. The high regions are not high for only one component."
      },
      {
        "heading": "BARMM and Central Visayas are low across major components",
        "body": "BARMM had the lowest any violent discipline level at 32.7 percent, followed by Central Visayas at 34.9 percent. BARMM was also lowest for psychological aggression at 27.7 percent, while Central Visayas was lowest for any physical punishment at 19.2 percent. These regions are low on both the summary measure and key components."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional gaps are much larger than sex or residence gaps",
        "body": "The regional range in any violent discipline runs from 70.9 percent in Davao Region to 32.7 percent in BARMM. That spread is much larger than the usual differences by sex or residence, making geography the main structure in this page. National averages therefore flatten very different regional discipline patterns."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Severe physical punishment is low but not absent",
        "body": "Severe physical punishment was 2.0 percent nationally in 2025, down from 3.4 percent in 2022. It is much less common than psychological aggression or any physical punishment, but it remains analytically important because it captures the harshest forms in the table. Its decline is one of the clearer improvements in the national profile."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Violent discipline declined from 2022 to 2025, but still affected more than half of children aged 1 to 14.",
      "Davao Region, Cagayan Valley, and Bicol Region have the highest levels of any violent discipline.",
      "BARMM and Central Visayas are lowest on the headline violent discipline measure.",
      "Non-violent discipline increased, but remains less common than any violent discipline nationally."
    ]
  }
